Project Idea¶

I implemented a similar project on much larger scale professionally at Admiral Markets (Now Admirals). The idea was to score all the customers that signed up within last 1-10 minutes on the company's website in all 10+ regions, so that the model(s) could categorize them into three categories

  1. Hot: having a large chance to convert to paid customer.
  2. Warm: having a medium chance to convert to paid customer.
  3. Cold: having a low chance to convert to paid customer.

The defintion of large/medium/low depends on actual dataset and its characteristics and on the business decision to decide how much work the sales team can handle. For example in my practical and real world application, we used the the following thresholds:

  • Above 70% probability to convert = Hot Lead
  • Between 33% and 70% probability to convert to paid = Warm Lead
  • Below 33% is Cold Lead

By using above thresholds we were able to provide sales team a sorted list of customers based on their probability to move to paid customer, so every 1-10 minutes they could decide how much workload they could handle.

I implemented the project end-to-end i.e I build the data engineering pipelines connecting our internal CRM and other systems to DataWareHouse, did all the data analysis steps for feature engineering, data cleaning, quality checks and worked with different stakeholders/teams to make sure the data distributions does not change in silo's, everyone is informed, build,tested and deployed the model on Google cloud and used our interal API's to send results to the relevant teams in the format expected by them. Also managed all the documentation, presentations to the stakeholders and trainings for relevant teams. A lot more was done which I wish not to continue writing in order to keep this project manageable.

The impact of the project was 70-90% reduction in sales work and we were able to use the results in different departments. For example Customer Service only handled calls from high potential i.e HOT leads. Marketing used to identify our ideal customer etc. All improvements while keeping our conversion rate stable.

Project Goals¶

From the dataset:

X Education wants to select the most promising leads, i.e. the leads that are most likely to convert into paying customers. The company requires you to build a model wherein you need to assign a lead score to each of the leads such that the customers with higher lead score h have a higher conversion chance and the customers with lower lead score have a lower conversion chance. The CEO, in particular, has given a ballpark of the target lead conversion rate to be around 80%.
div My Opinion:
I believe the lead scoring cannot help with improving the conversion rate itself. The issue is that we do not know on a given time frame what would be the quality of the leads that would sign up, hence the conversion rate depends how good we are at Identifying the Ideal Customer Profile and market them well. Lead Scoring can help with differentiation valuable vs not-valuable customers, so we could plan our sales and marketing efforts better. So, in this specific project, my goals are 1. Exploratory Data Analysis(EDA) 2. Test and Evaluate an automated EDA python library(sweetviz), as the dataset has 30+ columns and I wish to keep my time spend as productive as possible.
This library also calculates associations within categorical variable.( Reference 2)
3. Train a simple model(decision tree) and showcase how it could help with interpretability. Interpretability is important as for business its always good to know why a customer converts, hence can help identity the Ideal Customer Profile as well.

Data Dictionary¶

Observations from EDA¶

  1. ProspectID and LeadNumber Columns are just ways to identify each lead in the system. We can keep one as an index to our df.
  2. Most columns are categorical and only 5 of them are Numerical.
  3. LeadSource and LeadOrigin has strong association. So keeping only LeadOrigin. Also it has only one value for Quick Add Form Category, so replace this with Lead Add Form .
  4. DoNotCall: 99% values are No, So remove this column.
  5. TotalVisits: Replace missing values with mean as it is a continuous column. This is correlated to PageViewsPerVisit & TotalTimeSpentonWebsite. So Keeping only TotalVisits.
  6. LastActivity: Keep only top 6 values and replace mising values with one of them randomly. Strongly correlated to Magazine, ReceiveMoreUpdatesAboutOurCourses, UpdatemeonSupplyChainContent, GetupdatesonDMContent, Iagreetopaytheamountthroughcheque, LastNotableActivity, DoNotEmail. So keeping only LastActivity.
  7. Country: Since majority leads are from India, it does not provide much information about lead quality. Drop it.
  8. Specialization: keep only 4 top categories, move Select and others into single "Other" category.
  9. HowdidyouhearaboutXEducation: keep only 2 online search and Word of Mouth categories, lump others into 'Other' category.
  10. Whatisyourcurrentoccupation: keep only employed/unemployed categories.
  11. Whatmattersmosttoyouinchoosingacourse, Search, Magazine, NewspaperArticle, XEducationForums, Newspaper, DigitalAdvertisement, ThroughRecommendations, ReceiveMoreUpdatesAboutOurCourses,UpdatemeonSupplyChainContent,GetupdatesonDMContent, Iagreetopaytheamountthroughcheque: only single category, remove it.
  12. Tags, LeadQuality, LeadProfile: does not make sense on lead quality. Drop it.
  13. City: As most leads are from mumbai, does not make sense to keep this column.
  14. AsymmetriqueActivityIndex, AsymmetriqueProfileIndex, AsymmetriqueProfileScore, AsymmetriqueActivityScore: alot of missing values and no explanation provides. Drop it.
  15. AfreecopyofMasteringTheInterview: clean column with no missing or weird values.
  16. LastNotableActivity: since highly correlated to LastActivity. Drop it.
